@article{Oreshkov2011,
	Abstract = {Quantum detectors provide information about the microscopic properties of quantum systems by$\backslash$n establishing correlations between those properties and a set of macroscopically distinct events that$\backslash$n we observe. The question of how much information a quantum detector can extract from a system is$\backslash$n therefore of fundamental significance. In this paper, we address this question within a precise$\backslash$n framework: given a measurement apparatus implementing a specific POVM measurement, what is the$\backslash$n optimal performance achievable with it for a specific information readout task and what is the$\backslash$n optimal way to encode information in the quantum system in order to achieve this performance? We$\backslash$n consider some of the most common information transmission tasks---the Bayes cost problem, unambiguous$\backslash$n message discrimination and the maximal mutual information. We provide general solutions to the$\backslash$n Bayesian and unambiguous discrimination problems. We also show that the maximal mutual information$\backslash$n is equal to the classical capacity of the quantum-to-classical channel describing the measurement,$\backslash$n and study its properties in certain special cases. For a group covariant measurement, we show that$\backslash$n the problem is equivalent to the problem of accessible information of a group covariant ensemble of$\backslash$n states. We give analytical proofs of optimality in some relevant cases. The framework presented here$\backslash$n provides a natural way to characterize generalized quantum measurements in terms of their$\backslash$n information readout capabilities.},
